n exposed the misogyny they faced from publishers; and how children of literary parents have struggled with and benefited from their inheritances. Drawing on interviews and tens of thousands of pages of letters and manuscripts, The Literary Mafia offers striking new discoveries about celebrated figures such as Lionel Trilling and Gordon Lish, and neglected fiction by writers including Ivan Gold, Ann Birstein, and Trudy Gertler. In the end, we learn how the success of one minority group has lessons for all who would like to see American literature become more equitable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aJewish publisherszUnited States. 0aJewish publishingzUnited States. 0aJewszUnited StatesxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aPublishers and publishingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPublishers and publishingzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Books & Reading.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Comm 2022 Englishz978311099395008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Communication 2022z9783110994186oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z97831107497790 cprintz978030025142540uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300265354?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300265354423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300265354/original  a978-3-11-074977-9  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11